        "type": "Structural Flaws - Legal Contradiction",
        "original_text": "11.9 Severability If any provision of this Agreement is held to be invalid or unenforceable by a court of competent jurisdiction all other provisions shall continue in full force and effect. The Parties hereby agree to attempt to substitute for any invalid or unenforceable provision a valid and enforceable provision which achieves to the greatest extent possible the economic legal and commercial objectives of the invalid or unenforceable provision.",
        "changed_text": "8.2.5 Licenses to BII a. Freedom to operate XENCOR hereby grants to BII and BII herewith accepts a non exclusive, worldwide, irrevocable, sublicensable (in several cascades), perpetual, royalty-free/fully paid up license under the XENCOR Intellectual Property to the extent it is generally applicable to the manufacturing of biopharmaceutical products, handling 27 of cell lines and/or development of manufacturing processes, to use such XENCOR Intellectual Property in for the manufacture of biopharmaceutical products, handling of cell lines and/or development of manufacturing processes, but excluding any use with respect to the Product (or any modification, derivative or fragment thereof). BII expressly agrees not to practice any XENCOR Intellectual Property specific to the Product or for any purpose other than as expressly provided in this Section 8.2.5. 11.9 Severability If any provision of this Agreement is held to be invalid or unenforceable by a court of competent jurisdiction all other provisions shall continue in full force and effect. The Parties hereby agree to ignore any invalid or unenforceable provision, as the contract will remain in full force and effect regardless.",
        "explanation": "The original severability clause is in section 11.9. I have modified the text to state that the Parties hereby agree to ignore any invalid or unenforceable provision, as the contract will remain in full force and effect regardless. In the United States contract law, a severability clause ensures that the remainder of a contract remains valid and enforceable even if one or more of its provisions are found to be invalid, illegal, or unenforceable. This modification contradicts the standard function of severability clauses, which aim to replace or modify invalid provisions to maintain the contract's original intent, not simply ignore them.",
